blocks.text: July 22–24, 1966: Three of Cindy's friends in Washington, Mary Lynn Moody, Patty Jo Divers and Sandy Olson, come to Lancaster with Cindy. They are taken on a tour of the Amish country, see a covered bridge, and attend a flea market.
The old Clay Hotel. built in 1766. It is said that here the innkeeper's blindfolded daughter draw lots for a draft of local men for the Revolutionary army.

This obelisk, a few miles northwest of Mercersburg on a deeply wooded hillside, marks the spot where James Buchanan. 15th president of the United States was born in 1791. A remote spot even today, what must it have been like in 1791!

September thirty, through October two - Gordon and Kitty spend week end in Port Chester,
N. Y. with Jack and Mary Connolly.
Jack and Mary, spectators.

The basic idea seems to be to hit a wooden ball with a mallet through the opponents' goal while astride a horse or a polo pony. There are four players on each side. The field is a large 200 by 300 yards. Suggest field glasses the next time.

Sunday night with Kathy and John in Larchmont so that Kitty can visit Kathy's school next day to observe teaching methods. Gordon spends the day touring the Connecticut coast of Long Island Sound. (Left) Play of sunlight on small craft offshore.
